# Brick DSL

Brick is a typed, English-like language for browser automation. Files have the extension `.brick` and compile to `RunbookStep[]` via `brick build`.

## File structure

```brick
module MyModule

fn main() -> string {
  // statements
}
```

- Every function **must** start with the `fn` keyword
- The first function in the file is the entry point
- `module` declaration is optional but recommended

## Types

```brick
type Customer = {
  name: String
  email: String
  score: Number
}

type Status = "active" | "inactive" | "pending"
```

## Functions

```brick
fn main() -> string {
  // body
}

fn processRow(row: Customer) -> string {
  return @row.name
}
```

## Statements

### Navigation
```brick
navigate "https://example.com"
go to "https://example.com"
```

### Clicking
```brick
click "#submit-btn"
click "Submit" as "Submit button"
click "[data-testid='login']"
```

### Form input
```brick
fill "Email" with "user@example.com"
fill "Email" with @email
type "#input" with "text"
select "#dropdown" to "Option A"
```

### Keyboard
```brick
press Enter
press Tab
press "Escape"
```

### Waiting
```brick
wait 1s
wait 500ms
wait 2m
```

### Scrolling
```brick
scroll ".container" by 300
```

### Screenshots
```brick
screenshot -> @snap
```

### Variables
```brick
"hello world" -> @greeting
@count = 0
@count += 1
```

### Control flow
```brick
if @count > 5 {
  log "done"
} else {
  log "continue"
}

while @running == true {
  click "Next"
  wait 1s
}

for @row in @rows {
  navigate @row.url
}

repeat 3 {
  click "Retry"
  wait 2s
}
```

### JavaScript
```brick
js {
  return document.title;
} -> @title

js {
  return document.querySelector('.price').innerText;
} -> @price
```

### Python (with Playwright access)
```brick
python {
  result = await page.title()
} -> @title

python {
  # `variables` dict holds all @vars
  name = variables.get('name', '')
  result = name.upper()
} -> @upper_name
```

### AI generation
```brick
gen "Summarise this text: @content" -> @summary
gen "Extract the price from: @page_text" as Number -> @price
gen "Classify this email" using "gpt-4o" -> @classification

// Pass a variable as the full prompt
gen @my_prompt -> @result
```

### AI action
```brick
ai "Click the most prominent call-to-action button" -> @result
```

### Extraction
```brick
extract table "Product listings" -> @products
extract from @html "the total price" -> @total
```

### File operations
```brick
open_file "/path/to/file.pdf" -> @text
read_pdf "/path/to/file.pdf" -> @text
read_gdoc "https://docs.google.com/..." -> @text
load excel @file_path sheet "Sheet1" -> @data
load_sheet "My Sheet" -> @rows
```

### Import
```brick
import "src/helpers.brick"
```

### Logging / errors
```brick
log "Processing row @index"
fail "Could not find element"
```

### Return
```brick
return @result
```

## Variable interpolation

Use `@varname` anywhere a string is expected — in `navigate`, `gen`, `log`, and most statement arguments:

```brick
navigate @url
log "Found @count results for @query"
gen "Summarise: @content" -> @summary
```

## Common patterns

### Scrape and summarise
```brick
fn main() -> string {
  navigate "https://example.com/report"
  js {
    return document.body.innerText;
  } -> @body
  gen "Summarise this report in 3 bullet points:\n@body" -> @summary
  return @summary
}
```

### Loop through rows
```brick
fn main() -> string {
  load_sheet "Prospects" -> @rows
  for @row in @rows {
    navigate @row.url
    screenshot -> @snap
    ai "Fill in the contact form with name '@row.name' and email '@row.email'"
    wait 1s
  }
  return "Done"
}
```

### Conditional branching
```brick
fn main() -> string {
  navigate "https://app.example.com/status"
  js { return document.querySelector('.status').innerText; } -> @status
  if @status == "error" {
    screenshot -> @snap
    return "Error detected"
  }
  return "OK"
}
```

## Build & run

```bash
brick build          # compile src/main.brick → src/main.json
brick run            # run the compiled runbook
brick watch          # watch + rebuild on change
```
